Here's a complete Appwrite Function in Node.js that handles a JSON body with a `name` field and returns a personalized greeting:

```javascript
// src/main.js
export default async ({ req, res, log, error }) => {
    // Only allow POST requests for this endpoint
    if (req.method !== 'POST') {
        return res.json(
            { error: 'Method not allowed. Use POST.' },
            405
        );
    }

    // Parse the JSON body (req.bodyJson is the parsed object)
    const data = req.bodyJson;

    // Validate the "name" field
    if (!data?.name || typeof data.name !== 'string') {
        error('Missing or invalid "name" field');
        return res.json(
            { error: 'A "name" field (string) is required.' },
            400
        );
    }

    log(`Greeting user: ${data.name}`);

    // Return the personalized greeting
    return res.json({
        message: `Hello, ${data.name}! Welcome to Appwrite.`
    });
};
```

### Key points about the structure

**Function signature** — The entry point file (e.g. `src/main.js`) must `export default` an `async` function that destructures the context object:

| Property | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `req` | The incoming request |
| `res` | Helper to build the response |
| `log` | Logs info to the execution console |
| `error` | Logs errors to the execution console |

**Reading the body:**
- `req.bodyJson` — the **parsed** JSON object (cleanest for JSON payloads)
- `req.body` — the raw string body (parse manually with `JSON.parse` if you prefer)

**Response format** — Always `return` a response helper. `res.json(data, statusCode)` automatically sets the `Content-Type: application/json` header. Other options include `res.text()`, `res.empty()`, `res.redirect()`, and `res.send()`.

### Example request/response

Request body:
```json
{ "name": "Ada" }
```

Response:
```json
{ "message": "Hello, Ada! Welcome to Appwrite." }
```

### `package.json`

Make sure your `package.json` declares ES modules so `export default` works:

```json
{
  "type": "module",
  "main": "src/main.js"
}
```

When configuring the function in Appwrite, set the **entry point** to `src/main.js` and choose a Node.js runtime (e.g. `node-18.0`). If you don't use `"type": "module"`, switch to CommonJS syntax instead: `module.exports = async ({ req, res, log, error }) => { ... }`.

Here's complete code using the Appwrite Web SDK to create a bucket, upload a file, and get a preview URL—with permission configuration at each step.

> **Important note:** Creating a **bucket** is a server-only operation (it requires an API key and the `node-appwrite` SDK). The Web SDK (`appwrite`) **cannot** create buckets. So I've split this into two parts:
> 1. **Server-side** (`node-appwrite`) — create the bucket
> 2. **Client-side** (`appwrite`, Web SDK) — upload the file and get the preview URL

---

## 1. Create the bucket (server-side — required)

```typescript
// server.ts — run on your backend (Node.js)
import { Client, Storage, Permission, Role, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const adminClient = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]')
    .setKey(process.env.APPWRITE_API_KEY); // API key with buckets.write scope

const storage = new Storage(adminClient);

const bucket = await storage.createBucket({
    bucketId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'Images',
    // Bucket-level permissions — define default access for all files in the bucket
    permissions: [
        Permission.read(Role.any()),               // anyone can read files
        Permission.create(Role.users()),           // any logged-in user can upload
        Permission.update(Role.users()),
        Permission.delete(Role.users()),
    ],
    fileSecurity: true,                              // enable per-file permission overrides
    enabled: true,
    maximumFileSize: 10 * 1024 * 1024,               // 10 MB
    allowedFileExtensions: ['jpg', 'jpeg', 'png', 'webp', 'gif'],
});

console.log('Bucket created:', bucket.$id);
```

> `fileSecurity: true` lets the per-file permissions you set during upload take effect. If `false`, only bucket-level permissions apply.

---

## 2. Upload a file & get a preview URL (client-side — Web SDK)

```typescript
// app.ts — runs in the browser
import { Client, Storage, Permission, Role, ID } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const storage = new Storage(client);

const BUCKET_ID = '[BUCKET_ID]'; // the $id from step 1

async function uploadAndPreview(userId: string) {
    // Get the selected file from an <input type="file" id="file-input">
    const input = document.getElementById('file-input') as HTMLInputElement;
    const selectedFile = input.files![0];

    // Upload with per-file permissions
    const file = await storage.createFile({
        bucketId: BUCKET_ID,
        fileId: ID.unique(),
        file: selectedFile,
        permissions: [
            Permission.read(Role.any()),          // public read access
            Permission.update(Role.user(userId)), // only the owner can modify
            Permission.delete(Role.user(userId)), // only the owner can delete
        ],
    });

    console.log('Uploaded file ID:', file.$id);

    // Get a resized/optimized preview URL for the image
    const previewUrl = storage.getFilePreview({
        bucketId: BUCKET_ID,
        fileId: file.$id,
        width: 400,
        height: 400,
        // Optional transforms:
        // gravity: ImageGravity.Center,
        // quality: 80,
        // output: ImageFormat.Webp,
    });

    console.log('Preview URL:', previewUrl);

    // Use it directly in an <img>
    const img = document.createElement('img');
    img.src = previewUrl.toString();
    document.body.appendChild(img);

    return previewUrl;
}
```

---

### Key points

| Operation | SDK | Why |
|-----------|-----|-----|
| Create bucket | `node-appwrite` (server) | Requires an API key; not available in the Web SDK |
| Upload file | `appwrite` (Web) | User-context upload from a file input |
| Get preview URL | `appwrite` (Web) | `getFilePreview` returns a URL synchronously (no `await`) |

**Permission tips:**
- `getFilePreview` only works on **image** files (jpg, png, gif, webp, etc.).
- For the preview to load in a browser, the file needs `Permission.read(Role.any())` — otherwise the user must be authenticated and have read access.
- Per-file permissions (set during upload) only apply if the bucket has `fileSecurity: true`.

If you're working entirely client-side and the bucket already exists (created via the Appwrite Console or CLI), you only need step 2.

Here's code that subscribes to both table row changes and file uploads simultaneously, handling each event type differently:

```typescript
import { Client, Realtime, Channel } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const realtime = new Realtime(client);

const DATABASE_ID = '[DATABASE_ID]';
const TABLE_ID = '[TABLE_ID]';
const BUCKET_ID = '[BUCKET_ID]';

// Subscribe to BOTH channels in a single subscription
const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
    [
        Channel.tablesdb(DATABASE_ID).table(TABLE_ID).row(),
        Channel.bucket(BUCKET_ID).file(),
    ],
    (response) => {
        // Each event string looks like:
        //   'tablesdb.[DB].tables.[TABLE].rows.[ROW].create'
        //   'buckets.[BUCKET].files.[FILE].create'
        const events = response.events;

        // --- Route based on which resource the event belongs to ---

        // Table row events
        if (events.some((e) => e.includes('.rows.'))) {
            handleRowEvent(events, response.payload);
            return;
        }

        // File events
        if (events.some((e) => e.includes('.files.'))) {
            handleFileEvent(events, response.payload);
            return;
        }
    }
);

// ---- Handler for table row changes ----
function handleRowEvent(events: string[], payload: any) {
    if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.create'))) {
        console.log('Row created:', payload.$id, payload);
    } else if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.update'))) {
        console.log('Row updated:', payload.$id, payload);
    } else if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.delete'))) {
        console.log('Row deleted:', payload.$id);
    }
}

// ---- Handler for file uploads / changes ----
function handleFileEvent(events: string[], payload: any) {
    if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.create'))) {
        console.log('File uploaded:', payload.$id, payload.name, `${payload.sizeOriginal} bytes`);
    } else if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.update'))) {
        console.log('File updated:', payload.$id, payload.name);
    } else if (events.some((e) => e.endsWith('.delete'))) {
        console.log('File deleted:', payload.$id);
    }
}

// ---- Clean up when no longer needed ----
// await subscription.close();
```

### How it works

- **`realtime.subscribe([...channels], callback)`** accepts an array of channels, so a single subscription listens to both the table rows and the bucket files at once.
- The **callback's `response.events`** array contains event strings whose suffix (`.create`, `.update`, `.delete`) tells you the action, while the path segment (`.rows.` vs `.files.`) tells you the resource type.
- I route on resource type first, then branch on the specific action so each event type is handled differently.
- Calling **`subscription.close()`** unsubscribes from all channels in that subscription.

### Notes
- `Channel.tablesdb(db).table(id).row()` (no argument) targets *all* rows in the table; pass a row ID to scope to a single row.
- `Channel.bucket(id).file()` (no argument) targets *all* files in the bucket; pass a file ID to scope to a single file.
- The file payload (`Models.File`) exposes useful fields like `name`, `sizeOriginal`, `mimeType`, and `bucketId`.

If you'd prefer two **separate** subscriptions (e.g., so you can independently close one), let me know and I can show that variant too.

Here's a single `realtime.subscribe()` call listening to both a table's rows and a bucket's files:

```typescript
import { Client, Realtime, Channel } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const realtime = new Realtime(client);

const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
    [
        Channel.tablesdb('[DATABASE_ID]').table('[TABLE_ID]').row(),
        Channel.bucket('[BUCKET_ID]').file(),
    ],
    (response) => {
        console.log(response.channels); // which channel matched
        console.log(response.events);   // event(s) that fired
        console.log(response.payload);  // affected row or file
    }
);

// Later, to stop listening:
// await subscription.close();
```

## The exact channel strings

When the `Channel` helpers are resolved, they produce these literal strings:

| Resource | Channel string |
|----------|----------------|
| All rows in a table | `tablesdb.[DATABASE_ID].tables.[TABLE_ID].rows` |
| All files in a bucket | `buckets.[BUCKET_ID].files` |

So if you prefer, you can pass the raw strings directly instead of the builder:

```typescript
const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
    [
        'tablesdb.[DATABASE_ID].tables.[TABLE_ID].rows',
        'buckets.[BUCKET_ID].files',
    ],
    (response) => { /* ... */ }
);
```

**Notes:**
- Substitute your real IDs for the bracketed placeholders.
- To narrow to a single resource, append the ID: `tablesdb.[DATABASE_ID].tables.[TABLE_ID].rows.[ROW_ID]` or `buckets.[BUCKET_ID].files.[FILE_ID]`.
- The callback fires for events on **either** channel; use `response.channels` or `response.events` to distinguish which resource triggered it.

# Email/Password Auth with the Appwrite Web SDK

## 1. Install the SDK

```bash
npm install appwrite
```

## 2. Set up the client

```ts
// src/lib/appwrite.ts
import { Client, Account, ID } from 'appwrite';

export const client = new Client()
  .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1') // e.g. 'fra.cloud.appwrite.io/v1'
  .setProject('<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>');

export const account = new Account(client);
export { ID };
```

> Put `<REGION>` and `<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>` in env vars (e.g. `VITE_APPWRITE_ENDPOINT`, `VITE_APPWRITE_PROJECT_ID`) for any non-trivial app.

## 3. Sign up (create account)

```ts
import { AppwriteException } from 'appwrite';
import { account, ID } from './lib/appwrite';

export async function signUp(email: string, password: string, name: string) {
  try {
    const user = await account.create({
      userId: ID.unique(),
      email,
      password,
      name,
    });
    // Auto-login after signup (optional)
    await signIn(email, password);
    return user;
  } catch (err) {
    if (err instanceof AppwriteException) {
      // 409 = user already exists, 400 = weak password/validation, etc.
      throw new Error(err.message);
    }
    throw err;
  }
}
```

## 4. Sign in (create email/password session)

```ts
import { AppwriteException } from 'appwrite';
import { account } from './lib/appwrite';

export async function signIn(email: string, password: string) {
  try {
    const session = await account.createEmailPasswordSession({
      email,
      password,
    });
    return session; // { $id, userId, secret, expire, ... }
  } catch (err) {
    if (err instanceof AppwriteException) {
      // 401 = invalid credentials, 429 = rate limited
      throw new Error(err.message);
    }
    throw err;
  }
}
```

## 5. Get the current user / sign out

```ts
import { account } from './lib/appwrite';

export async function getCurrentUser() {
  try {
    return await account.get();
  } catch {
    return null; // no active session
  }
}

export async function signOut() {
  await account.deleteSession({ sessionId: 'current' });
}
```

## 6. Putting it together in a component

```tsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import { signUp, signIn } from './auth';

export default function AuthForm() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
  const [name, setName] = useState('');
  const [mode, setMode] = useState<'signup' | 'login'>('signup');
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  async function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {
    e.preventDefault();
    setError(null);
    try {
      if (mode === 'signup') {
        await signUp(email, password, name);
      } else {
        await signIn(email, password);
      }
      // Navigate to your protected page
    } catch (err) {
      setError((err as Error).message);
    }
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      {mode === 'signup' && (
        <input
          type="text"
          placeholder="Name"
          value={name}
          onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
          required
        />
      )}
      <input
        type="email"
        placeholder="Email"
        value={email}
        onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
        required
      />
      <input
        type="password"
        placeholder="Password (min 8 chars)"
        minLength={8}
        value={password}
        onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
        required
      />
      <button type="submit">
        {mode === 'signup' ? 'Create account' : 'Sign in'}
      </button>
      <button type="button" onClick={() => setMode(mode === 'signup' ? 'login' : 'signup')}>
        Switch to {mode === 'signup' ? 'login' : 'signup'}
      </button>
      {error && <p style={{ color: 'red' }}>{error}</p>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

## Key gotchas

- **Email/password auth must be enabled** in your Appwrite Console → *Auth → Settings*.
- **`createEmailPasswordSession`** is the dedicated method — don't reuse `createSession` (that's for OAuth tokens). On Appwrite Cloud, sessions are limited to 100 per user (oldest is pruned on the 101st).
- **Password rules** (enforced server-side): minimum 8 chars by default. If you get a `400` on signup, check the console's auth settings.
- **Use `ID.unique()`** for `userId` unless you have a reason to supply your own (e.g. matching an external system).
- For SSR (Next.js, SvelteKit, etc.) you can't use the web SDK directly — see the SSR section in the docs and use `node-appwrite` with cookies named `a_session_<PROJECT_ID>`.

# Appwrite Web SDK — Create Database, Table, and Row

> **Important:** Creating databases and tables are **server-side only** operations that require an API key. Use the server SDK (`node-appwrite`) for setup, or call the web SDK from a backend with an API key. Client-side apps (browser/mobile) can only create rows, not databases or tables.

Here's a complete, runnable script that uses the `appwrite` package (Web SDK) to do everything end-to-end. If you want to run this in the browser, skip the `create` calls and pre-create the database/table on the server.

## Installation

```bash
npm install appwrite
```

## Code

```ts
import { Client, TablesDB, ID, Permission, Role } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1') // e.g. 'https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1'
    .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>')
    .setKey('<API_KEY>'); // Required for createDatabase / createTable

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

async function main() {
    // 1) Create the database (server-side only)
    const database = await tablesDB.create({
        databaseId: ID.unique(),
        name: 'TaskTracker',
    });
    const databaseId = database.$id;
    console.log('Created database:', databaseId);

    // 2) Create the "tasks" table with columns
    const table = await tablesDB.createTable({
        databaseId,
        tableId: ID.unique(),
        name: 'tasks',
        columns: [
            { key: 'title',     type: 'varchar',  size: 255, required: true  },
            { key: 'completed', type: 'boolean',            required: false, default: false },
            { key: 'dueDate',   type: 'datetime',           required: false },
        ],
    });
    const tableId = table.$id;
    console.log('Created table:', tableId);

    // 3) Insert a row
    const row = await tablesDB.createRow({
        databaseId,
        tableId,
        rowId: ID.unique(),
        data: {
            title: 'Write Appwrite quickstart',
            completed: false,
            dueDate: new Date('2026-02-01T17:00:00.000Z').toISOString(),
        },
        permissions: [
            Permission.read(Role.any()),
            Permission.update(Role.any()),
            Permission.delete(Role.any()),
        ],
    });

    console.log('Created row:', row);
}

main().catch((err) => console.error(err));
```

## Column types used

| Column    | Type       | Notes                                                      |
|-----------|------------|------------------------------------------------------------|
| `title`     | `varchar`  | Inline string, max 16,383 chars; fully indexable.          |
| `completed` | `boolean`  | `true` / `false`.                                          |
| `dueDate`   | `datetime` | ISO 8601 string, e.g. `"2026-02-01T17:00:00.000Z"`.        |

## Browser-only variant (rows only)

If you want to do the row insert from the browser using a logged-in user, drop the API key and use a session instead. The `create` and `createTable` calls must be removed (do them once on the server first):

```ts
import { Client, TablesDB, ID, Permission, Role } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

const row = await tablesDB.createRow({
    databaseId: '<DATABASE_ID>',
    tableId: '<TABLE_ID>',
    rowId: ID.unique(),
    data: {
        title: 'Buy groceries',
        completed: false,
        dueDate: '2026-02-15T10:00:00.000Z',
    },
    permissions: [
        Permission.read(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
        Permission.update(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
        Permission.delete(Role.user('<USER_ID>')),
    ],
});
```

## Tips

- **Idempotency:** If you re-run the script, capture the generated `databaseId` and `tableId` and reuse them instead of calling `create` again.
- **Permissions:** Rows inherit table-level permissions by default. Only set `permissions` on `createRow` when you need per-row overrides.
- **Object-params style:** This SDK uses named parameters (`{ databaseId, tableId, ... }`) — preferred over positional arguments for readability.

# Querying Rows in Appwrite TablesDB with the `Query` Class

The `Query` class (imported alongside `TablesDB`) builds query strings that you pass in the `queries` array to `tablesDB.listRows()`. Each method returns a query object — combine as many as you need; by default they are joined with **AND**.

## Setup

```typescript
import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'appwrite';
// Server-side: import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

const response = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
    queries: [
        // build queries here
    ]
});

response.documents; // row objects
response.total;     // total count
```

---

## 1. Filtering

### Equality & inequality
```typescript
Query.equal('status', 'active')        // status == 'active'
Query.notEqual('status', 'archived')   // status != 'archived'

// Pass an array for IN queries
Query.equal('role', ['admin', 'editor'])  // role IN ('admin', 'editor')
```

### Numeric / date comparisons
```typescript
Query.lessThan('age', 30)
Query.lessThanEqual('age', 30)
Query.greaterThan('age', 18)
Query.greaterThanEqual('age', 18)
Query.between('age', 18, 65)          // 18 <= age <= 65
```

### Null checks
```typescript
Query.isNull('deletedAt')
Query.isNotNull('avatarUrl')
```

### String matching
```typescript
Query.startsWith('name', 'Al')         // "Alice", "Alex", ...
Query.endsWith('email', '@appwrite.io')
Query.contains('tags', 'featured')     // works on string contains or array contains
```

### Full-text search
```typescript
Query.search('body', 'appwrite tutorial') // requires a full-text index on the column
```

### Logical composition
```typescript
// Explicit AND (queries are already AND-joined by default)
Query.and([
    Query.greaterThan('age', 18),
    Query.lessThan('age', 65)
])

// OR
Query.or([
    Query.equal('role', 'admin'),
    Query.equal('role', 'editor')
])
```

**Example — combine filters:**
```typescript
const results = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [
        Query.equal('status', 'published'),
        Query.greaterThanEqual('views', 100),
        Query.or([
            Query.startsWith('title', 'Appwrite'),
            Query.contains('tags', 'featured')
        ])
    ]
});
```

---

## 2. Sorting

```typescript
Query.orderAsc('createdAt')
Query.orderDesc('views')
```

**Example — newest published first:**
```typescript
const results = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [
        Query.equal('status', 'published'),
        Query.orderDesc('createdAt')
    ]
});
```

> The order of sort fields determines priority — earlier sorts win over later ones. To sort by multiple fields, add multiple `orderAsc`/`orderDesc` calls in the desired priority order.

---

## 3. Limiting

`Query.limit()` caps the number of rows returned in a single response.

```typescript
Query.limit(25) // default is 25, max is 100
```

**Example — top 10 most-viewed:**
```typescript
const top = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [
        Query.equal('status', 'published'),
        Query.orderDesc('views'),
        Query.limit(10)
    ]
});
```

**Selecting specific fields** (also a kind of "limit" on the response payload):
```typescript
queries: [Query.select(['title', 'summary', 'author'])]
```

---

## 4. Pagination

There are two strategies: **offset** (simple, but slow on large datasets) and **cursor** (recommended for large datasets).

### Offset-based
```typescript
const page1 = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [Query.limit(25), Query.offset(0)]
});

const page2 = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [Query.limit(25), Query.offset(25)]
});
```

`response.total` contains the total number of rows matching your filters, which you can use to compute total pages.

### Cursor-based (preferred for large datasets)
Cursor pagination uses the `$id` of the last/first row from the previous page — it's stable and fast even with millions of rows.

```typescript
// First page
const first = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [Query.limit(25), Query.orderDesc('$createdAt')]
});

// Next page — pass the last row's ID
const lastId = first.documents[first.documents.length - 1].$id;
const second = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [Query.limit(25), Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'), Query.cursorAfter(lastId)]
});

// Walk backwards with cursorBefore
const previous = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: 'articles',
    queries: [Query.limit(25), Query.orderDesc('$createdAt'), Query.cursorBefore(firstId)]
});
```

---

## Putting it all together

A realistic search/list page query that filters, sorts, paginates, and shapes the response:

```typescript
async function searchArticles({ search, page = 0, perPage = 20 }) {
    const queries = [
        Query.equal('status', 'published'),
    ];

    if (search) queries.push(Query.search('title', search));

    queries.push(
        Query.orderDesc('publishedAt'),
        Query.limit(perPage),
        Query.offset(page * perPage),
        Query.select(['$id', 'title', 'summary', 'author', 'publishedAt'])
    );

    const res = await tablesDB.listRows({
        databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
        tableId: 'articles',
        queries
    });

    return {
        rows: res.documents,
        total: res.total,
        hasMore: (page + 1) * perPage < res.total
    };
}
```

**Tips:**
- The default `Query.limit()` is **25**, the maximum is **100**. For more, use pagination.
- You can combine as many queries as you need — there's no artificial cap, but more filters can affect index usage.
- For frequently-queried fields, make sure your columns have appropriate indexes configured in the Appwrite Console.
- Prefer **cursor pagination** (`cursorAfter` / `cursorBefore`) over `offset` for any dataset that may grow large.

# Filtering and Sorting Rows with Query

Appwrite's `Query` helper lets you compose filter, sort, and pagination conditions that you pass as an array to `listRows`. Multiple queries are combined with **AND** by default, so you can just stack them.

## The Three Queries You Need

```typescript
Query.greaterThan('price', 100)   // Filter:  field > 100
Query.orderDesc('price')         // Sort:    field descending
Query.limit(20)                  // Page:    return at most 20 rows
```

## Full Example

```typescript
import { Client, TablesDB, Query } from 'appwrite';        // or 'node-appwrite' server-side

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const tablesDB = new TablesDB(client);

const results = await tablesDB.listRows({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
    queries: [
        Query.greaterThan('price', 100),
        Query.orderDesc('price'),
        Query.limit(20),
    ],
});

console.log(results.documents); // up to 20 rows, highest price first
console.log(results.total);     // total matching rows (ignores limit)
```

## How It Works

- **`Query.greaterThan('price', 100)`** — keeps only rows whose `price` is strictly greater than 100. Use `Query.greaterThanEqual(...)` if you want `>= 100`.
- **`Query.orderDesc('price')`** — sorts the matching rows by `price` from largest to smallest. For the opposite order, use `Query.orderAsc('price')`.
- **`Query.limit(20)`** — caps the result set at 20 rows. The hard maximum is 100; if you need more, paginate with `Query.offset()` or, for large datasets, prefer `Query.cursorAfter('[ROW_ID]')` for stable, efficient paging.
- **Order doesn't matter** within the `queries` array — Appwrite applies filters first, then sorts, then paginates.

## Common Variations

```typescript
// Include 100: field >= 100
Query.greaterThanEqual('price', 100)

// Range filter
Query.greaterThan('price', 100), Query.lessThan('price', 500)

// Paginate the next page
Query.limit(20), Query.offset(20)

// Cursor-based pagination (more efficient for large tables)
Query.limit(20), Query.cursorAfter(lastRowIdFromPreviousPage)
```

## Tip: Make It Type-Safe

For full TypeScript inference on the returned rows, pass a generic interface to `listRows<T>`:

```typescript
interface Product {
    name: string;
    price: number;
}

const results = await tablesDB.listRows<Product>({
    databaseId: '[DATABASE_ID]',
    tableId: '[TABLE_ID]',
    queries: [Query.greaterThan('price', 100), Query.orderDesc('price'), Query.limit(20)],
});

results.documents[0].price; // typed as number
```

> **Note:** For consistent performance, ensure the column you're filtering/sorting on has an index configured in your table settings. Sorting on unindexed columns works but can be slow on large tables.

```js
// src/main.js
export default async function ({ req, res, log, error }) {
  try {
    // req.body is automatically parsed when Content-Type is application/json
    const { name } = req.body;

    if (!name || typeof name !== "string") {
      return res.json(
        {
          ok: false,
          message: 'Missing or invalid "name" field in request body.',
        },
        400,
      );
    }

    log(`Greeting requested for: ${name}`);

    return res.json({
      ok: true,
      message: `Hello, ${name}! Welcome to Appwrite Functions.`,
      name,
    });
  } catch (err) {
    error("Failed to handle greeting request: " + err.message);
    return res.json(
      { ok: false, message: "Internal server error." },
      500,
    );
  }
}
```

### How it works

Appwrite Functions in Node.js export a default async function that receives a single context object with these properties:

| Property | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `req` | The incoming request. `req.body` is auto-parsed for `application/json`, `req.bodyRaw` gives the raw string, and `req.query` / `req.headers` / `req.method` / `req.path` are also available. |
| `res` | The response object. Use `res.json(payload, statusCode)` to return JSON, plus `res.text()`, `res.send()`, `res.empty()`, `res.redirect()`, `res.binary()`. |
| `log(...)` | Writes an info-level log visible in the execution log. |
| `error(...)` | Writes an error-level log. |

`res.json()` accepts `(payload, statusCode)` where `statusCode` defaults to `200`, which is why the error branches pass `400` and `500`.

### `package.json` (optional, in the function folder)

```json
{
  "type": "module",
  "main": "src/main.js"
}
```

The `"type": "module"` setting lets you use the `export default` syntax. If you prefer CommonJS, use:

```js
// src/main.js (CommonJS variant)
module.exports = async function ({ req, res, log, error }) {
  // ...same body as above
};
```

### Deploy it

From your `appwrite.config.json` add the function definition:

```json
{
  "functions": [
    {
      "$id": "greeting",
      "name": "Greeting",
      "runtime": "node-22",
      "entrypoint": "src/main.js",
      "path": "functions/greeting",
      "commands": "npm install"
    }
  ]
}
```

Then run:

```bash
appwrite push functions --function-id greeting --activate
```

### Invoke it

```bash
appwrite functions create-execution \
  --function-id greeting \
  --body '{"name":"Ada"}'
```

Response:

```json
{
  "ok": true,
  "message": "Hello, Ada! Welcome to Appwrite Functions.",
  "name": "Ada"
}
```

A few notes:
- You don't need any SDK dependency to read `req.body` — Appwrite parses JSON for you.
- For binary or streaming responses, use `res.binary()` or `res.send()` with a buffer/stream.
- For scheduled or event-driven invocations, `req.body` will contain the Appwrite event payload; the same handler works as long as you validate the input.

# Appwrite Web SDK: Bucket, Upload & Image Preview

Creating a bucket is a **server-side admin operation** (requires an API key), while file uploads and previews are typically done **client-side**. Here's a complete solution using both:

## 1. Create the Bucket (Server-side / Admin)

```typescript
// server.ts — uses the server SDK with an API key
import { Client, Storage, ID, Permission, Role } from 'node-appwrite';

const adminClient = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject(process.env.APPWRITE_PROJECT_ID!)
    .setKey(process.env.APPWRITE_API_KEY!);

const storage = new Storage(adminClient);

const bucket = await storage.createBucket({
    bucketId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'User Avatars',
    permissions: [
        Permission.read(Role.any()),        // public read so preview URLs work
        Permission.create(Role.users()),    // any logged-in user can upload
        Permission.update(Role.users()),
        Permission.delete(Role.users()),
    ],
    fileSecurity: true,                    // enable per-file permissions
    enabled: true,
    maximumFileSize: 10 * 1024 * 1024,     // 10 MB
    allowedFileExtensions: ['jpg', 'jpeg', 'png', 'gif', 'webp'],
});

console.log('Bucket created:', bucket.$id);
```

## 2. Upload a File & Get Preview URL (Client-side)

```typescript
// client.ts — uses the Web SDK in the browser
import { Client, Storage, ID, Permission, Role } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('<PROJECT_ID>');

const storage = new Storage(client);

async function uploadImage(bucketId: string, userId: string) {
    // Pick file from <input type="file" id="file-input" accept="image/*">
    const fileInput = document.getElementById('file-input') as HTMLInputElement;
    if (!fileInput.files?.[0]) throw new Error('No file selected');

    // Upload with per-file permissions
    const file = await storage.createFile({
        bucketId,
        fileId: ID.unique(),
        file: fileInput.files[0],
        permissions: [
            Permission.read(Role.any()),              // public preview
            Permission.update(Role.user(userId)),     // owner can update
            Permission.delete(Role.user(userId)),     // owner can delete
        ],
    });

    // Generate preview URL (returns a URL object — usable in <img src>)
    const preview = storage.getFilePreview({
        bucketId,
        fileId: file.$id,
        width: 400,                                  // resize
        height: 400,
        gravity: 'center',                           // 'center' | 'top-left' | etc.
        quality: 80,
        borderRadius: 8,                             // optional rounded crop
        output: 'jpg',                               // 'jpg' | 'png' | 'webp' | 'gif'
    });

    return { file, previewUrl: preview.toString() };
}

// Usage
const { file, previewUrl } = await uploadImage('<BUCKET_ID>', '<USER_ID>');

document.querySelector('img')!.src = previewUrl;
console.log('File ID:', file.$id);
```

## Key Points

| Concern | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Bucket creation** | Server-side only — must use `node-appwrite` with an API key |
| **Bucket-level permissions** | Set once at creation; default for all files inside |
| **File-level permissions** | Override per-file — requires `fileSecurity: true` on the bucket |
| **`Permission.read(Role.any())`** | Required on either the bucket OR the file for `getFilePreview` to work publicly |
| **Preview URL** | Returned synchronously by `getFilePreview()` — no network call. Pipe it directly into `<img src>`, `fetch()`, etc. |
| **Image processing** | `width`, `height`, `quality`, `gravity`, `borderRadius`, and `output` are all optional |

## Permissions Cheat-Sheet

```typescript
// Common patterns
Permission.read(Role.any())                          // public, including guests
Permission.read(Role.users())                        // any authenticated user
Permission.read(Role.user(userId))                   // specific user
Permission.read(Role.team(teamId))                   // any team member
Permission.read(Role.team(teamId, 'editor'))         // members with a specific role

Permission.write(Role.user(userId))                  // create + update + delete
Permission.update(Role.user(userId))                 // update only
Permission.delete(Role.user(userId))                 // delete only
```

> ⚠️ **Common mistake:** Setting `Permission.read(Role.any())` only on individual files but forgetting to enable `fileSecurity: true` on the bucket — the file-level permissions will be ignored.

# Appwrite Storage: `getFileView()` vs `getFileDownload()` vs `getFilePreview()`

All three methods generate a **URL string** (not the file data itself) that you assign to an `<img>`, `<a>`, `window.open()`, etc. The key differences are in **how the file is served** and **what transformations apply**.

## 1. `storage.getFileView()`

Returns a URL that serves the file **inline** (in the browser) with `Content-Disposition: inline`. Works for **any file type** — PDFs, videos, audio, images, etc. No transformations are applied.

```typescript
const result = storage.getFileView({
    bucketId: '[BUCKET_ID]',
    fileId: '[FILE_ID]'
});
// -> 'https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1/storage/buckets/.../files/.../view'
```

**Use when:** You want users to *view* a file in the browser tab without forcing a download. For example, opening a PDF invoice, playing a video, or displaying a file's content directly in an iframe.

## 2. `storage.getFileDownload()`

Returns a URL that serves the file with `Content-Disposition: attachment`, **forcing the browser to download** it. Works for **any file type**. No transformations.

```typescript
const result = storage.getFileDownload({
    bucketId: '[BUCKET_ID]',
    fileId: '[FILE_ID]'
});
// -> 'https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1/storage/buckets/.../files/.../download'
```

**Use when:** You want the user to save a copy locally — e.g., a "Download Report" button, exporting a CSV, downloading a ZIP.

> Note: In the browser SDK this returns a `URL` object; on the server SDK you typically fetch the bytes directly.

## 3. `storage.getFilePreview()`

Returns a URL for a **transformed image preview**. Only works for **image files** (PNG, JPG, WebP, etc.) and supports manipulation parameters like `width`, `height`, `gravity`, `quality`, `border`, `opacity`, `rotation`, `background`, and `output` format.

```typescript
const preview = storage.getFilePreview({
    bucketId: '[BUCKET_ID]',
    fileId: '[FILE_ID]',
    width: 300,
    height: 300,
    gravity: 'center',
    quality: 80,
    output: 'webp'
});
// -> 'https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1/storage/buckets/.../files/.../preview?width=300&...'
```

**Use when:** You need a **resized/optimized image variant** — e.g., avatar thumbnails in a user list, card cover images, or any place where loading the full-resolution original would be wasteful.

## Quick Comparison

| Method | File types | Transformations | Browser behavior |
|---|---|---|---|
| `getFileView()` | Any | ❌ None | Display inline |
| `getFileDownload()` | Any | ❌ None | Force download |
| `getFilePreview()` | Images only | ✅ Resize, crop, quality, format, etc. | Display inline (as image) |

## Practical Examples

```typescript
// User avatar thumbnail in a list
<img src={storage.getFilePreview({
    bucketId: 'avatars',
    fileId: user.avatarId,
    width: 64, height: 64, gravity: 'face'
}).toString()} />

// "View PDF" button
<a href={storage.getFileView({
    bucketId: 'documents',
    fileId: invoice.fileId
}).toString()} target="_blank">View Invoice</a>

// "Download CSV" button
<a href={storage.getFileDownload({
    bucketId: 'exports',
    fileId: export.fileId
}).toString()}>Download Report</a>
```

**Rule of thumb:**
- Need a resized image? → `getFilePreview`
- Want the original file shown in the browser? → `getFileView`
- Want the original file saved to disk? → `getFileDownload`

# Subscribing to Realtime Table Rows and File Uploads

The Appwrite Web SDK lets you subscribe to multiple channels in a single `subscribe()` call, then branch on `response.events` to handle each kind of change. The event strings follow a predictable pattern (`tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.<action>` and `buckets.*.files.*.<action>`), which makes routing easy.

## Install

```bash
npm install appwrite
```

## Full example

```ts
import { Client, Realtime, Channel } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const realtime = new Realtime(client);

// Subscribe to a table's rows AND a bucket's files in one call.
// Each response includes `events`, `payload`, `channels`, and `timestamp`.
const channels = [
    Channel.tablesdb('[DATABASE_ID]').table('[TABLE_ID]').row(), // all rows in the table
    Channel.bucket('[BUCKET_ID]').file(),                       // all files in the bucket
];

const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(channels, (response) => {
    // Every event in Appwrite realtime is namespaced. Branching on the
    // first event is sufficient because the SDK delivers one logical
    // change per callback invocation.
    const event = response.events[0];

    if (event?.startsWith('tablesdb.')) {
        handleRowEvent(event, response.payload);
    } else if (event?.startsWith('buckets.')) {
        handleFileEvent(event, response.payload);
    } else {
        console.warn('Unhandled event:', event);
    }
});

function handleRowEvent(event: string, payload: any) {
    if (event.endsWith('.create')) {
        // e.g. "tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.create"
        console.log('🆕 Row created:', payload.$id, payload);
        // Example: prepend to a list, show a toast, etc.
    } else if (event.endsWith('.update')) {
        // e.g. "tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.update"
        console.log('✏️  Row updated:', payload.$id, payload);
        // Example: patch the row in a local cache by $id
    } else if (event.endsWith('.delete')) {
        // e.g. "tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.delete"
        console.log('🗑️  Row deleted:', payload.$id);
        // Example: remove from local state
    }
}

function handleFileEvent(event: string, payload: any) {
    if (event.endsWith('.create')) {
        // e.g. "buckets.*.files.*.create"
        console.log('📤 File uploaded:', payload.name, payload.$id);
        // Example: show progress, refresh gallery, generate a preview URL
        // const preview = storage.getFilePreview({ bucketId: '[BUCKET_ID]', fileId: payload.$id, width: 300, height: 300 });
    } else if (event.endsWith('.update')) {
        console.log('📝 File metadata updated:', payload.$id, payload);
    } else if (event.endsWith('.delete')) {
        console.log('🗑️  File deleted:', payload.$id);
    }
}

// Later — when the user navigates away or the component unmounts:
await subscription.close();
```

## How it works

**Channel selection.** `Channel.tablesdb(db).table(t).row()` listens to every row in that table. To watch a single row instead, call `.row('[ROW_ID]')`. For storage, `.file()` covers the whole bucket, and `.file('[FILE_ID]')` targets one file.

**Multiple channels, one callback.** Pass an array of channels to a single `subscribe()` call. The callback fires once per change, and `response.channels` tells you which channel(s) matched. Branching on `response.events[0]` is the standard way to route — every event in Appwrite is namespaced (`tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.<action>` and `buckets.*.files.*.<action>`), so a `startsWith` check is enough to dispatch.

**The payload.** For row events, `payload` is the affected `Models.Document` (with `$id`, `$createdAt`, `$updatedAt`, plus your columns). For file events, it's the `Models.File` metadata object (with `$id`, `name`, `mimeType`, `sizeOriginal`, `buckets` IDs, etc.) — not the file bytes.

**Cleanup.** `subscription.close()` removes the underlying WebSocket subscription. Call it when the component unmounts or the user leaves the page so you don't leak listeners.

**Tip:** if you want to be more selective, you can also subscribe to a specific row (`Channel.tablesdb(db).table(t).row('[ROW_ID]')`) or a specific file (`Channel.bucket(b).file('[FILE_ID]')`) to avoid being woken up by unrelated changes.

# Single `realtime.subscribe()` for TablesDB rows + Storage files

You pass an **array of channels** to one `subscribe()` call. Use the `Channel` builder to construct the channel strings safely (it stringifies to the exact format Appwrite expects).

```ts
import { Client, Realtime, Channel } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('[PROJECT_ID]');

const realtime = new Realtime(client);

const subscription = await realtime.subscribe(
    [
        Channel.tablesdb('[DATABASE_ID]').table('[TABLE_ID]').row(),
        Channel.bucket('[BUCKET_ID]').file(),
    ],
    (response) => {
        console.log(response.events);   // e.g. ['tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.create']
        console.log(response.payload);  // the affected row or file
    }
);

// Later:
await subscription.close();
```

## Exact channel strings (raw form)

| Builder expression | Underlying channel string |
|---|---|
| `Channel.tablesdb('DB_ID').table('TABLE_ID').row()` | `tablesdb.DB_ID.tables.TABLE_ID.rows` |
| `Channel.bucket('BUCKET_ID').file()` | `buckets.BUCKET_ID.files` |

## What you'll receive

A single callback fires for events on **either** channel. Distinguish them via `response.channels` (the matched channels) or `response.events`, e.g.:

- `tablesdb.*.tables.*.rows.*.create` / `.update` / `.delete` — row events
- `buckets.*.files.*.create` / `.update` / `.delete` — file events

> 💡 You can also subscribe to a **specific** row or file by passing an ID:
> `Channel.tablesdb('DB_ID').table('TABLE_ID').row('ROW_ID')` → `tablesdb.DB_ID.tables.TABLE_ID.rows.ROW_ID`
> `Channel.bucket('BUCKET_ID').file('FILE_ID')` → `buckets.BUCKET_ID.files.FILE_ID`
